'''National symbols of Sri Lanka''' are the symbols that represent the country and its people within Sri Lanka and abroad. They are National Anthem, National Flag, National Flower, National Tree, National Emblem, National Bird, National Dress, etc.<ref>[http://www.mysrilanka.com/travel/lanka/nati_symbol/ National symbols of Sri Lanka]</ref>

==National symbols==
{|class="wikitable"
|-
! Title 
! Symbol 
! width=100 | Media
! Notes
|-
| [[List of national anthems|National anthem]] 
| [[National anthem of Sri Lanka]]
| align="center"| [[File:Sri Lanka Matha.ogg|70px]]
| National anthem of Sri Lanka so called ''Sri Lanka Matha'' was written and composed by the Ananda Samarakoon in 1940, and was later adopted as the national anthem in 1951.<ref>Prabhu, R. K. (1967). ''Songs of freedom: An anthology of national and international songs from various countries of the world''. Bombay: Popular Prakashan. page 138</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Bandaranayake | first = Senake | title = Ivan Peries paintings, 1938-88 | publisher = Tamarind Publications | location = Colombo | year = 1996 | isbn = 9559458000 }} page 155</ref>
|-
| [[National flag|National Flag]]
| [[Flag of Sri Lanka]]
| align="center"| [[File:Flag of Sri Lanka.svg|70px]] 
| The National flag of Sri Lanka consists of a gold lion, holding a sword, in front of a dark red background with four golden bo leaves, one in each corner. Around the background is a yellow border, and to its left are 2 vertical stripes of equal size in green and saffron. It was adopted in 1950.
|-
| [[National emblem|National Emblem]] 
| [[Emblem of Sri Lanka|National Emblem of Sri Lanka]]
| align="center"| [[File:Emblem of Sri Lanka.svg|70px]] 
| The national emblem of Sri Lanka is used by Sri Lankan government in connection with the administration and government of the country. The current emblem has been in use since 1972. 
|-
| [[National flower]] 
| [[Red and blue water lily|Blue water lily]] or (''[[Nymphaea nouchali]]'')
| align="center"| [[File:Nymphaea Caerula.jpg|70px]]
| The Red and blue water lily was declared the National Flower of Sri Lanka on 26 February 1986.<ref name=govlk>[http://www.labour.gov.lk/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=192:customer-awareness-program-for-importers-of-chilled-canned-fish&catid=45:news&Itemid=166&lang=en National symbols of Sri Lanka - gov.lk]</ref> It found all the part of Sri Lanka and grows in the shallow water.
|-
| [[National tree]] 
| [[Ceylon ironwood]] or (''[[Mesua ferrea]]'')
| align="center"| [[File:MesuaFerrea IronWood.jpg|70px]]
| Ceylon ironwood was declared the National Tree on 26 February 1986. It was chosen as the National Tree for the reasons of tree origin in Sri Lanka, utility, historic & cultural importance, eExterior posture, wide distribution, colour & nature and ability to draw & sketch it easily.<ref name=govlk/>
|-
| [[National bird]] 
| [[Sri Lanka Junglefowl]] or (''Gallus lafayetii'')
| align="center"| [[File:Flickr - Rainbirder - Ceylon Junglefowl (Gallus lafayetii) Male.jpg|70px]] 
| Sri Lanka Junglefowl is colorful ground bird, endemic to Sri Lanka, and distributed commonly in Sri Lanka's jungle and dense scrub through out. 
|-
| [[National gemstone]] 
| [[Blue Sapphire]] 
| align="center"| [[File:Geschliffener blauer Saphir.jpg|70px]]
| The Blue Sapphire was declared as the National gemstone of Sri Lanka in October 2003.  Postage stamp worth of Rs 4.50 issued on 2 October 2003 to mark the announcement.<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/040314/funday/4.html Blue Sapphire - the national gemstone]</ref>
|-
| [[National butterfly]] 
| [[Troides darsius|Sri Lankan Birdwing]] or (''Troides darsius'')
| align="center"| [[File:Darsius female.jpg|70px]]
| The Sri Lankan Birdwing is a species of birdwing butterfly found in Sri Lanka. It is the largest Sri Lankan butterfly with a wingspan spreading 165<U+2013>180&nbsp;mm. The declaration of a national butterfly is aimed at raising public concern on butterfly conservation.<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/100328/News/nws_16.html Sri Lanka names its national butterfly]</ref><ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100404/FunDay/fut_05.html Our National Butterfly]</ref> 
|-
| [[National sport]] 
| [[Volleyball]] 
| align="center"| [[File:Volley ball angelo gelmi 01.svg|70px]]
| The volleyball officially recognized as the National Game of Sri Lanka in 1991.<ref>[http://volleyballsrilanka.org/ Introductory message from the President SLVF]</ref> Before volleyball was made the National game, <U+2018>Elle<U+2019> had been having recognition as a de facto National Sport.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=34318 Volleyball, Sri Lanka<U+2019>s National Sport]</ref>
|}

==Unofficial==
{|class="wikitable"
|-
! Title 
! Symbol 
! width=100 | Media
! Notes
|-
| [[National animal]] 
| [[Sri Lankan elephant]] or (''Elephas maximus maximus'') 
| align="center"| [[File:Sri Lanka Elephants.JPG|70px]] 
| There is no official declaration on the national animal of Sri Lanka. Even though, Sri Lankan elephant, Lion or [[Grizzled giant squirrel]] are unofficially claimed as national animal. Lion is not endemic animal. It is believed that there was [[Sri Lanka lion]], a prehistoric subspecies of lion.
|-
| [[National monument]] 
| [[Independence Memorial Hall]] 
| align="center"| [[File:Independence Commemoration Hall.jpg|70px]]
| Independence Memorial Hall is built for commemoration of the independence of Sri Lanka from the British rule with the establishment of Dominion of Ceylon on February 4, 1948. It also called as Independence Commemoration Hall and Independence Commemoration Hall.
|}

